# Initialising the CNN
classifier = keras.models.Sequential()

# Step 1 - Convolution
classifier.add(L.Convolution2D(32, 3, 3, input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3), activation = 'relu'))

# Step 2 - Pooling
classifier.add(L.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

# Adding a second convolutional block
classifier.add(L.Convolution2D(32, 3, 3, activation = 'relu'))
classifier.add(L.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

# Step 3 - Flattening
classifier.add(L.Flatten())

# Step 4 - Full connection
classifier.add(L.Dense(128, activation = 'relu'))
classifier.add(L.Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

# Compiling the CNN
classifier.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])

# Part 2 - Fitting the CNN to the images

from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale = 1./255,
                                   shear_range = 0.2,
                                   zoom_range = 0.2,
                                   horizontal_flip = True)

test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale = 1./255)
training_set = train_datagen.flow_from_directory('../input/cat-and-dog/training_set/training_set',
                                                 target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                                 batch_size = 32,
                                                 class_mode = 'binary')

test_set = test_datagen.flow_from_directory('../input/cat-and-dog/test_set/test_set',
                                            target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                            batch_size = 32,
                                            class_mode = 'binary')
chckpt_path = 'model.CNN.hdf5'

chckpt  = keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(chckpt_path, save_best_only=True,monitor = 'val_accuracy',mode='max')
classifier.fit_generator(training_set,
                         steps_per_epoch = len_train_set/32,
                         epochs = 10,
                         validation_data = test_set,
                         validation_steps = len_test_set/32,
                         callbacks=[chckpt]
                         )

def VGG():
    model = keras.applications.VGG16(include_top=False,weights='imagenet',input_shape=(250,250,3))
    new_output = keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(model.output)

    new_output = keras.layers.Dense(256,activation='relu')(new_output)
    new_output = keras.layers.Dense(64,activation='relu')(new_output)
    new_output = keras.layers.Dense(1,activation='sigmoid')(new_output)

    model = keras.engine.training.Model(model.inputs,new_output)
    return model

Transfer learning is a research area in machine learning where the objective is to use the knowledge gained in solving one problem in solving other related or similar problems. For example can a model trained to recognize cars be used to recognize trucks? 
In our case we will try to use a model trained on the image net dataset for a much smaller task of identifying cats and dogs. Image net is a famous(iconic to be honest) that contains millions of images and about a thousand classes, ranging from plants and animals to everyday objects and people. Our task at hand is somewhat a related problem.

## What is the VGG Model?
The VGG model was proposed in 2014 by the Visual Geometry Group Lab of Oxford university. In the ILSVRC competition that year it achieved the 1st and 2nd position in the two categories respectively.
> The VGG16 model is a deep convolutional model with 5 convolutional blocks. The original VGG16 model had 134 million parameters and took 2-3 weeks to train.
* More about the VGG models may be found [here](https://www.robots.ox.ac.uk/~vgg/research/very_deep/)

This notebook is an introduction to the process of transfer learning. I have attempted to provide an intuitive explanation of what transfer learning is and why one should use it. In order to keep it simple, I have used the cat and dog dataset to demonstrate the benefit of using transfer learning. So let's dive right in.
# Objectives
* To demonstrate that highly skilled deep learning models can be trained even with small datasets
* To demonstrate that very complex models with millions of parameters may be fine tuned to solve the problem at hand
* To demonstrate that complex models with pre-trained weights may be fine tuned in very less time (minutes instead of weeks) and with lesser resources

Before we proceed further, a question that comes to mind is why use transfer learning at all? 
* Training complex models on large datasets is computationally very expensive. Therfore such pre-trained models may be used with transfer learning for related tasks to achieve high performance with lesser amount of resources.
> 
* Even with less amount of data, training of higly skilled models is possible using tranfer learning.

There are various other benifits and uses of transfer learning.
